<font color="#FF0000">ANZAC</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct 30 21:37:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Thanks for the thoughts. I was with the last NZ Infantry unit to leave Vietnam in 1971 - V6 Coy 4RAR/NZ ANZAC as a Section M79 / Medic. We served in Phuoc Tuy Province. Like you all, Nam has influenced my life ever since - some good some bad. Some memories I keep locked up tight, but mostly OK. We were all volunteer professional soldiers. Thought I had my act together before I went - came home rather more confused. Came home to protests but also to a very proud older WW2 generation - that helped. Worked, building an orphanage in Vung Tau with Aussie Engineers towards the end of the tour which was probably the only decent thing I did over there.<br>
 On discharge I joined the NZ Fire Service putting all the adrenaline overdoses and medic training to good use. Proved a mentally satisfying, socially acceptable come down from combat. I believe I would have been a mess without that release.<br>
 NZ is holding a coming home parade in wellington next year - &quot;Parade 98&quot;. There are a number of US members of our Ex - Vietnam Veterans Association (EVSA) coming over. We just might be able to put it all to rest. The dialogue with the old protesters and the new generation is showing promise of healing some of this 30 year old trauma. Come and join us.  
<p><code>-- ralexand@dcc.govt.nz  (Rex Alexander) </code><p>


